<paragraph id="B92C36C1FFA66B3CAE302419FCEA4E00" blockId="18.[269,844,296,353]" box="[269,844,296,320]" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">
<heading id="E26481ADFFA66B3CAE302419FCEA4E00" box="[269,844,296,320]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="18" pageNumber="499" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="7E934D42FFA66B3CAE302419FCEA4E00" authority="Larsen and Patterson, 1990" authorityName="Larsen and Patterson" authorityYear="1990" box="[269,844,296,320]" class="Euglenoidea" family="Peranemaceae" genus="Heteronema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peranemida" pageId="18" pageNumber="499" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="exaratum">
<emphasis id="8BE7EAD3FFA66B3CAE302419FDAE4E00" bold="true" box="[269,520,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">Heteronema exaratum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="DD024B30FFA66B3CAD2C2418FCEA4E00" author="LARSEN, J. &amp; PATTERSON, D. J." box="[529,844,296,320]" pageId="18" pageNumber="499" pagination="937" refId="ref41333" refString="LARSEN, J. and PATTERSON, D. J., 1990, Some ¯ agellates (Protista) from tropical marine sediments, Journal of Natural History, 24, 801 ± 937." type="journal article" year="1990">Larsen and Patterson, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B92C36C1FFA66B3CAEF62479FD294E20" blockId="18.[269,844,296,353]" box="[459,655,328,353]" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">(®gures 6a, 7a±e)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F189654AFFA66B3AAF452449FC914E40" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="501" pageId="18" pageNumber="499" type="description">
<paragraph id="B92C36C1FFA66B3CAF452449FDBA4DEE" blockId="18.[79,1035,375,750]" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis id="8BE7EAD3FFA66B3CAF452449FF5B4ECF" box="[120,253,376,399]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">Description.</emphasis>
Cell ovate, 8±18 Mm long, 6±13 Mm wide, dorso-ventrall y ¯attened, metabolic, but not vigorously so, with a small ingestion organelle. With pellicular striations following a S-helix on both faces of the cell. The dorsal striations are more strongly developed than the ventral ones. This species usually moves by skidding in a counter-clockwise direction. Two ¯agella are similar in length, are slightly longer than the cell and point in diOEerent directions when moving; the anterior ¯agellum points to the right, the posterior ¯agellum to the left. The posterior ¯agellum has a knob at its base within the ¯agellar pocket and is stronger than the anterior ¯agellum. In immotile cells, the ¯agella coil up. The reservoir and nucleus are in the left side of the cell. Common.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B92C36C1FFA66B3AAF452786FC914E40" blockId="18.[79,1035,375,750]" lastBlockId="20.[79,1034,137,256]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="501" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis id="8BE7EAD3FFA66B3CAF452786FF444D8F" box="[120,226,695,719]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species has been found in marine sites in subtropical and tropical 
<collectingCountry id="C1847651FFA66B3CAF7227E7FF114DAE" box="[79,183,726,750]" name="Australia" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">Australia</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="C1847651FFA66B3CAFC027E7FE824DAE" box="[253,292,726,750]" name="Fiji" pageId="18" pageNumber="499">Fiji</collectingCountry>
with previously reported lengths from 15 to 20 Mm (
<bibRefCitation id="DD024B30FFA66B3DACB427E6FEA6497C" author="LARSEN, J. &amp; PATTERSON, D. J." lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="500" pageId="18" pageNumber="499" pagination="937" refId="ref41333" refString="LARSEN, J. and PATTERSON, D. J., 1990, Some ¯ agellates (Protista) from tropical marine sediments, Journal of Natural History, 24, 801 ± 937." type="journal article" year="1990">Larsen and Patterson, 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="DD024B30FFA76B3DAE2F2315FDC4497C" author="PATTERSON, D. J. &amp; SIMPSON, A. G. B." box="[274,610,1572,1596]" pageId="19" pageNumber="500" pagination="448" refId="ref42397" refString="PATTERSON, D. J. and SIMPSON, A. G. B., 1996, Heterotrophic ¯ agellates from coastal marine and hypersaline sediments in Western Australia, European Journal of Protistology, 32, 423 ± 448." type="journal article" year="1996">Patterson and Simpson, 1996</bibRefCitation>
). We have observed cells 8 Mm long, and although we have not seen an ingestion organelle the cells are otherwise in agreement with previous accounts of 
<taxonomicName id="7E934D42FFA76B3DAD322355FD06493B" authorityName="Larsen and Patterson" authorityYear="1990" box="[527,672,1636,1659]" class="Euglenoidea" family="Peranemaceae" genus="Heteronema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peranemida" pageId="19" pageNumber="500" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="exaratum">
<emphasis id="8BE7EAD3FFA76B3DAD322355FD06493B" box="[527,672,1636,1659]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="500">H. exaratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species can be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="7E934D42FFA76B3DAFAD23B5FF5249DB" authorityName="sensu KahlDsee" authorityYear="1928" box="[144,244,1667,1691]" class="Euglenoidea" family="Peranemaceae" genus="Heteronema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peranemida" pageId="19" pageNumber="500" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="ovale">
<emphasis id="8BE7EAD3FFA76B3DAFAD23B5FF5249DB" box="[144,244,1667,1691]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="500">H. ovale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see remarks to 
<taxonomicName id="7E934D42FFA76B3DAEF123B5FD9649DB" authorityName="sensu KahlDsee" authorityYear="1928" box="[460,560,1667,1691]" class="Euglenoidea" family="Peranemaceae" genus="Heteronema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peranemida" pageId="19" pageNumber="500" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="ovale">
<emphasis id="8BE7EAD3FFA76B3DAEF123B5FD9649DB" box="[460,560,1667,1691]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="500">H. ovale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), but is distinguished by less vigorous squirming, the more weakly developed pellicular striations, and the diOEerences between dorsal and ventral striations. It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="7E934D42FFA06B3AAC7D2598FC0A4F80" authorityName="Lee and Patterson" authorityYear="2000" box="[832,940,168,192]" class="Euglenoidea" family="Peranemaceae" genus="Heteronema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peranemida" pageId="20" pageNumber="501" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="larseni">
<emphasis id="8BE7EAD3FFA06B3AAC7D2598FC0A4F80" box="[832,940,168,192]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="501">H. larseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(below) because 
<taxonomicName id="7E934D42FFA06B3AAF8E25F8FEE54FA0" authorityName="Larsen and Patterson" authorityYear="1990" box="[179,323,201,224]" class="Euglenoidea" family="Peranemaceae" genus="Heteronema" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Peranemida" pageId="20" pageNumber="501" phylum="Euglenozoa" rank="species" species="exaratum">
<emphasis id="8BE7EAD3FFA06B3AAF8E25F8FEE54FA0" box="[179,323,201,224]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="501">H. exaratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has weaker pellicular striations, is smaller, does not have a pointed posterior end, and has a less visible ingestion apparatus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
